## Cerebellum

The cerebellum is a region of the brain that is responsible for coordinating movement. It is located at the back of the brain, just above the brainstem. The cerebellum consists of two hemispheres, each of which is divided into three lobes. The lobes are separated by deep fissures. The cerebellum has a highly convoluted surface, which is covered by a thin layer of tissue called the cerebellar cortex. This cortex is responsible for processing information from the rest of the brain and body. The cerebellum also contains a number of deep nuclei, which are responsible for controlling movement.

It receives input from the motor cortex, the vestibular system, and proprioceptors.

## Thalmaus
- All sensory information to cortex comes through thalamus
- Collection of ~15 nuclei which process
  - Visual
  - Auditory
  - Somatosensory
  - Some motor information

- Thalamocortical loops reciprocally connected with cerebral cortex
- Primary relay thalamic nuclei receive cortical input from primary sensory cortex
- Higher order thalamic nuclei integrate sensory cortex output and project to association cortex

## Basal Ganglia
- Collection of subcortical nuclei deep in white matter
  - Caudate 
  - Putamen 
  - Globus pallidus
  - substantia nigra
  - subthalamic nucleus

- Important for 
    - Control of movement - smooth the transitions of muscle contractions 
    - learning and motivation

### Basal Ganglia and Movement
- Caudate and putamen receive excitatory inputs from motor cortex, thalamus and brainstem
- Many neurotransmitters in basal ganglia (GABA, domapine, Ach) but output from globus pallidus to thalamus is inhibitory 
- Brake hypothesis 
